I want to plan and execute a large-scale analysis project focused on our Palo Alto Panorama environment. The goal is to use temporary, tightly scoped read and export API access so Claude can comprehensively review and inventory the full firewall management estate without making any configuration changes. This would include pulling and analyzing items such as device groups, templates, template stacks, interfaces, zones, VLANs, virtual routers, routing configuration, address objects, address groups, service objects, service groups, tags, NAT rules, security rules, policy layers, and any other relevant Panorama-managed configuration data. The purpose is to transform a large, difficult-to-review security environment into a clear, structured, and well-documented representation of how it is actually configured today.

From that collected data, I want Claude to generate high-quality artifacts that would normally take significant manual effort from network and security engineers. That includes structured inventory documentation, architecture summaries, relationship mappings between objects and policies, and clear network/security diagrams that visualize zones, routing boundaries, trust relationships, major policy flows, and how different parts of the environment connect. I also want the project to produce practical assessment outputs, such as reports identifying overly permissive firewall rules, unused or redundant objects, stale configurations, rule sprawl, policy shadowing, inconsistent naming or organization, segmentation weaknesses, and any other security or operational risks that become apparent through a full configuration review.

This project is meant to be read-only, analysis-focused, and documentation-heavy. I want Claude to help plan the safest and most effective approach for collecting the Panorama data, organizing it into a normalized structure, and then turning that into useful deliverables for engineering, security leadership, and future operational use. The end state should be a repeatable process that can take a complex Panorama deployment and produce comprehensive documentation, meaningful diagrams, and actionable security assessment reports with far less manual effort than a traditional review.
